article.description: The two highest-scoring teams in the league again made defense an afterthought.
article.headline: Another offense-filled game between Suns, Sonics
article.linkText: Suns' offense comes out on top in high-scoring game
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Tim Thomas is still learning his role on the Phoenix Suns. On Tuesday night, he got a lesson in just how fast his new team can play. Thomas shot 10-for-11 and scored 23 points off the bench, Shawn Marion scored 24 points with 11 rebounds, and the Phoenix Suns beat the Seattle SuperSonics 129-120. The two highest-scoring teams in the league again made defense an afterthought. Earlier this season, the teams combined for the highest-scoring game in the league in 11 years, a 152-149 Seattle victory in double overtime. This time, Thomas joined in. Playing his seventh game since coming to Phoenix, the forward scored 15 points in the first quarter and made his first 10 shots, as the Suns rebounded from a surprising loss in Portland on Sunday. "I'm just going with the flow now. I'd seen tape of the previous game and knew how high the score was," Thomas said. "It's just a matter of me getting a better feel each and every game with my own teammates and my own sets here." Raja Bell made 10 of 13 shots for 25 points as the Suns shot 56 percent. Steve Nash added 23 points and Boris Diaw scored 16 with nine rebounds and seven assists as Phoenix won for the 13th time in the last 15. It was the first time Seattle allowed an opponent to have four players score more than 20 points since Dec. 17, 2004, also against the Suns. "That was as fast as it's been since we played them last," Bell said. "Playing them, obviously it's going to be a quicker-paced game, but we've been coming out sluggish." The last time the teams met, Ray Allen made a 30-footer at the buzzer to give Seattle the win, capping a 42-point night. Allen did his part again, leading Seattle with 33 points, but Seattle could not match the Suns' scoring depth. Rashard Lewis added 22 for the Sonics, and Luke Ridnour had 19 points and 13 assists. "All we had to do was play a little bit of defense for one quarter," Lewis said. "We scored enough points to win the ballgame." Thomas had started four of his six games since signing with Phoenix, but coach Mike D'Antoni went with James Jones on Tuesday. D'Antoni quickly turned to Thomas, who made his first six shots. His half was shortened when he picked up his third foul, but Thomas continued his strong shooting in the second half, making 10 straight at one point. Phoenix scored 48 points in the paint, many coming on unimpeded drives by Nash, Leandro Barbosa and Eddie House. When they did meet resistance, Phoenix had plenty of shooters ready. Bell made five 3-pointers and Thomas added three. At one point in the first half, Phoenix was on pace for 60 3-point attempts. "That tempo helps us," Bell said. "We don't get bogged down and it's hard to guard guys when you're in transition all night." It didn't take much for Phoenix to finally build a comfortable advantage. Seattle pulled to 76-71 early in the third, but the Suns scored 10 of the next 14 points. Suddenly, the lead was 11 and the Sonics struggled to chip away. The lead grew to 14 on Marion's two free throws to start the fourth quarter and reached 108-92 after Thomas made his ninth consecutive basket. Seattle mounted one final run midway through the fourth. The Sonics outscored Phoenix 13-6 over a 4:09 span to trim the lead to 118-110, capped by Allen's 3-pointer. But Diaw took away all momentum, dribbling the length of the court and dunking to push the lead back to 10. "They played an awfully good game," Seattle coach Bob Hill said. "It thought our guys played hard, we just struggled to defend them." In their last meeting, the teams combined for 32 3-pointers, breaking the mark of 31 set by Toronto and Philadelphia on March 13, 2005. The 301 points were the most in a game since Dallas beat Houston 156-147 in two overtimes on April 11, 1995, according to the Elias Sports Bureau. It was the first 150-point game in the NBA since the Los Angeles Clippers beat Toronto 152-120 on March 15, 1998. Yet, most in the Seattle area were oblivious to the Sonics surprising, record win in Phoenix. It happened to fall on the same evening the Seattle Seahawks won the NFC championship by beating the Carolina Panthers.

Game notes
Hill and D'Antoni's relationship goes back to Italy. For Thanksgiving one year, D'Antoni invited all the Americans playing and coaching, including Hill, to his home in Milan. "His wife was awesome, cooked us this huge meal. It was such a neat day," Hill recalled. ... Nash, who grew up in nearby Victoria, British Columbia, received a loud ovation when introduced.
